---
import DocsLayout from '../../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import Callout from '../../../../components/Callout.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../../../../components/CodeBlock.astro';
---

<DocsLayout title="Testing" description="Test the full store with Stripe test payments, webhook handling, and API verification.">
  <h1 class="mb-6">Testing</h1>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">You know the testing step. Project 4 adds a new layer: testing third-party integrations with real (test-mode) transactions and verifying API compliance.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Automated tests</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Direct Claude to generate tests from your PRD. At minimum:</p>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-6">
    <li><strong class="text-text">API tests:</strong> Product catalog endpoints, search, cart operations</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Cart logic:</strong> Add, remove, update quantity, calculate total</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Payment flow:</strong> Stripe Checkout session creation (mocked in unit tests, real in integration tests)</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Manual testing</h2>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-6">
    <li>Search and filtering — try various artist names, genres, partial matches</li>
    <li>Add items to cart, update quantities, remove items</li>
    <li>Complete checkout end-to-end with Stripe test card <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">4242 4242 4242 4242</code></li>
    <li>Order confirmation page shows correct details</li>
    <li>Order confirmation email sends with correct content</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">API-specific testing</h2>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Stripe webhook handling</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Use the <a href="https://docs.stripe.com/stripe-cli">Stripe CLI</a> to trigger test webhook events:</p>
  <CodeBlock lang="bash" copy>{`stripe listen --forward-to localhost:8000/api/webhooks/stripe`}</CodeBlock>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Then make a test payment and verify:</p>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-6">
    <li>Webhook event arrives at your endpoint</li>
    <li>Your code correctly parses the event</li>
    <li>Order status updates in the database</li>
    <li>Confirmation email triggers</li>
  </ul>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Google Maps</h3>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-6">
    <li>Map loads on the store location page</li>
    <li>Pin is at the correct location (Fitzroy, Melbourne — verify visually)</li>
    <li>Map displays correctly on mobile</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Stripe test cards</h2>
  <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
    <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
      <thead>
        <tr class="bg-bg-muted">
          <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold border-b border-border">Card Number</th>
          <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold border-b border-border">What It Tests</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr class="border-b border-border">
          <td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono">4242 4242 4242 4242</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Successful payment</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border bg-bg-subtle">
          <td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono">4000 0000 0000 0002</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Card declined</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border">
          <td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono">4000 0000 0000 3220</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">3D Secure authentication required</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Edge cases</h2>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-6">
    <li><strong class="text-text">Empty cart checkout</strong> — does the app prevent it?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Out-of-stock item</strong> — what happens if stock runs out between adding to cart and checking out?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Network error during payment</strong> — does the app handle Stripe being unreachable?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Invalid card number</strong> — does the error message make sense to the user?</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Lighthouse audit</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Album art can be heavy. Run a Lighthouse audit with focus on:</p>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-6">
    <li><strong class="text-text">Image optimization</strong> — are album art images properly sized and compressed?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">LCP (Largest Contentful Paint)</strong> — product images are likely the LCP element. Are they lazy-loaded where appropriate?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Core Web Vitals</strong> — CLS from images loading, FID from JavaScript</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">End-to-end tests with Playwright</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Unit tests and manual testing check individual pieces. End-to-end (E2E) tests check the entire user flow — from browsing to payment — in a real browser.</p>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Playwright opens a real browser and automates what a user would do. It clicks buttons, fills forms, and checks results. When these tests pass in CI, you know the user flow works.</p>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Tell Claude Code to write Playwright tests for the checkout flow:</p>

  <CodeBlock copy>{`Write Playwright E2E tests for the checkout flow:
1. Browse the product catalog
2. Add a record to the cart
3. Go to checkout
4. Complete payment with Stripe test card 4242 4242 4242 4242
5. Verify the order confirmation page appears with correct details

Use Playwright's test runner. Each step should wait for the page to load before proceeding.`}</CodeBlock>

  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Run the tests locally to verify they pass. If a test fails, it usually means the flow is broken — which is exactly the kind of thing you want to catch before deployment.</p>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>The new testing layer:</strong> Projects 1-3 tested your code. Project 4 also tests your integrations. A payment flow that uses a hallucinated Stripe parameter will fail silently or produce confusing errors. The docs check during building should have caught these — testing confirms it.</p>
  </Callout>

  <details class="my-8 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary class="px-6 py-4 bg-bg-muted cursor-pointer font-semibold text-sm">The landscape: end-to-end testing</summary>
    <div class="px-6 py-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4">Playwright is the modern default for E2E testing, but it's not the only option.</p>
      <div class="space-y-3">
        <div><p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Playwright</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Microsoft's browser automation tool. Supports Chromium, Firefox, and WebKit. Fast, reliable, and actively maintained. What you're using in this project.</span></p></div>
        <div><p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Cypress</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Popular alternative with a clean API and built-in time-travel debugging. Runs in-browser rather than controlling it externally. Large community and plugin ecosystem.</span></p></div>
        <div><p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Selenium</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">The original browser automation framework. Supports every browser and language. Still widely used in enterprise. Slower and more verbose than modern alternatives.</span></p></div>
        <div><p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Puppeteer</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Google's Node.js library for controlling Chrome/Chromium. Lightweight and fast, but Chrome-only. Good for scraping and screenshots, less feature-rich for testing.</span></p></div>
        <div><p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">TestCafe</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">No WebDriver dependency — injects scripts directly into the page. Simple setup, cross-browser, but smaller community than Playwright or Cypress.</span></p></div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mt-4">Playwright and Cypress are the two serious contenders for new projects. Either works well. Playwright's multi-browser support and Microsoft backing make it a safe default.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <div class="mt-8 p-6 bg-primary-bg rounded-lg border border-primary/20 text-center">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-2">Next: deploy to staging</h2>
    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Tests pass. Time to deploy with API keys configured in production.</p>
    <a
      href="/web-dev/projects/4/deployment"
      class="inline-block bg-primary hover:bg-primary-dark text-white font-semibold py-3 px-6 rounded-md transition-colors min-h-[44px]"
    >
      Deployment →
    </a>
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
